In article <CDsFuI.67L@news.claremont.edu> ebrandt@jarthur.claremont.edu (Eli Brandt) writes:
>In article <27qfat$qdm@apple.com> James Zuchelli <James_Zuchelli*@BBCOMM.apple.com> writes:
>>Well if one-time pads are unbreakable, why don't they just use them and
>>not worry about PGP which may very well be easily broken by the people
>>who break codes for a living?
>
>(Unless there is a problem in the keygen routines, this seems unlikely.)
>
>Well, one-time pads *are* used.  They're expensive and inconvenient,
>of course.  Besides that, the security of [OTP plus transferring a
>gigabyte of of key material] may well be less than that of [RSA+IDEA
>plus transferring a kilobyte of key material].
>
Easiest way to break a one-time pad is to bribe someone who has access to
it. Next easiest is probably to steal a copy........ The same goes for a lot
of security measures: the weakest link can often be a human one.

Dave
